        "text": "Al Without loss of generality, assume d, ≤ d2 ≤ ... ≤ d12. it2 < di+d? i+1 for some i ≤ 10, then di, di+1, di+2 are the side lengths of an acute triangle, since in this cased < di + diz and di <d+ di2 as well. Thus we may assume dizz ≥ di + dit for all i. But then by induction, df > Fidf for all i, where F; is the i-th Fibonacci number (with F1 = F2 = 1): i = 1 is clear, i = 2 follows from d2 ≥ di, and the induction step follows from the assumed inequality. Setting i = 12 now gives di2 = 144d}, contradicting di > 1 and d12 < 12.",
