      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_2012_Solutions_2012s_page_001_13",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "We now return to the original problem. By dividing B, q,r by ged(q,r) if necessary, we may reduce to the case where gcd (q,r) = 1. We may assume #S ≥ 3, as otherwise S is trivially an arithmetic progression. Let a1, a2, a3 be any three distinct elements of S, labeled so that a1 < a2 < a3, and write ra; = bi + mig with bi, m; E Z and b; € B. Note that by, b2, b3 must also be distinct, so the differences b2 - b1, b3 - b1,b3 - b2 are all nonzero; consequently, two of them have the same sign. If bi - bj and bk - by have the same sign, then we must have",
        "bbox": [
          0.5581228602136111,
          0.2978670637124882,
          0.9191729340438677,
          0.45547866720603886
        ],
        "order": 5
